\begin_layout Subsection
Flight responses to pulses of different durations 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How does the duration of the odor pulse encountered affect behavioral responses?
 Due to the relatively high speed at which Drosophila fly (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim30$
\end_inset

 cm/s) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Tammero:2002wd"

\end_inset

and the relatively narrow width of odor plumes that they would likely encounter
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Murlis:1981by,Murlis:1992kp,Murlis:2000kk,Justus:2002da"

\end_inset

, flies may experience contact and loss witha plume almost instatneously.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vanBreugel:2014is"

\end_inset

.
 This suggests that flies may modulate their behavior even to very brief
 plumes of odorant.
 To test this hypothesis, I presented flies with pulses of ethyl acetate
 odorant with varying durations.
\end_layout

